{"key":"post-20133500","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>20133500</id>\n<content>The freezing water tells them the season is over and it's time to go dormant for the winter.&amp;nbsp; This is why around 45F to 50F is perfect for cold shocking.&amp;nbsp; It tells them cold weather is coming so they better act busy.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You probably can't do shiitake during the summer in those temps.&amp;nbsp; Grow elm oysters or something heat tolerant and grow your shiitake during the winter months.&amp;nbsp; In my location, I can grow them outdoors all summer because even when we get into the 90s during the day, it still drops to the lower 40s at night.&amp;nbsp; I can take blocks straight from colonization to a shady spot along the creek and they fruit right away.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The blocks below are spent substrates of varying ages that were put by the creek, where they fruit for several years until the sawdust is completely consumed.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-27/163947372-outdoor_shiitake.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/12-27/163947372-thumb_outdoor_shiitake.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-32/437029127-Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate3.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/12-32/437029127-thumb_Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate3.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-32/437029090-Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; targe